compared with this one:

    @Autowired
    public void configureGlobal(AuthenticationManagerBuilder auth) throws Exception {
        KeycloakAuthenticationProvider ap = new KeycloakAuthenticationProvider;
        ap.setGrantedAithoritiesMapper(new SimpleAuthorityMapper());
        auth.authenticationProvider(ap);
    }

Both code snippets are configuring Keycloak authentication for a Spring Security application, but with a slight difference in how the KeycloakAuthenticationProvider is created and set up.

In the first code snippet:

    @Autowired
    public void configureGlobal(AuthenticationManagerBuilder auth) throws Exception {
        auth.authenticationProvider(keycloakAuthenticationProvider());
    }

The KeycloakAuthenticationProvider is created by calling a method named `keycloakAuthenticationProvider()`. This method is not provided in the code snippet, so it can be assumed that it might be provided somewhere else in the codebase, probably returning a preconfigured KeycloakAuthenticationProvider instance.

In the second code snippet:

    @Autowired
    public void configureGlobal(AuthenticationManagerBuilder auth) throws Exception {
        KeycloakAuthenticationProvider ap = new KeycloakAuthenticationProvider();
        ap.setGrantedAuthoritiesMapper(new SimpleAuthorityMapper());
        auth.authenticationProvider(ap);
    }

The KeycloakAuthenticationProvider is created explicitly with a new instance and configured with a SimpleAuthorityMapper directly in the method. The SimpleAuthorityMapper is used to map Keycloak roles to Spring Security authorities.

In summary, both code snippets achieve a similar goal but differ in the way the KeycloakAuthenticationProvider instance is created and set up. The first one relies on a separate method (not provided in the snippet), while the second one explicitly initializes and configures the provider within the `configureGlobal` method.

